synopsis: Idle GC and deadlock detection in the non-threaded RTS now behave the same as in the threaded RTS
description: {
Idle GC now works in the non-threaded RTS and is enabled by default.

Deadlock detection in the non-threaded RTS now follows the same design and
behaviour as in the threaded RTS. In particular, it can detect partial
deadlocks where some but not all threads are deadlocked. The detection is no
longer prompt however, as the detection runs as part of idle GC, which (by
default) is performed 0.3 seconds after all capabilities become idle.

The user guide now documents that deadlock detection relies on idle GC,
and thus turning off idle GC disables deadlock detection. This is true
of the threaded RTS in previous GHC releases but it was not previously
documented behaviour.

Internally, the idle GC and deadlock detection now follow the same design and
use 99% the same code between the non-threaded and threaded RTS. Having a
single design improves the comprehension and maintainability of the RTS code.
}
